postcontent:
It's tough letting your children go, but the time has come. I need a sidefolder AK74 in my life in a bad way, and the safe is getting crowded with 7.62 guns. 

I built this one a few months back with mostly Romanian and Egyptian surplus AKM parts on a McKay/NoDak receiver. Probably one of the smoothest AKs I've ever built. Note that this is not some pile of junk screwed/welded/nailed/glued together hillbilly rig. I rivet my builds together correctly with a 20-ton hydraulic press and test fire the hell out of them. No junk here.

Parts breakdown:
Gas block, front sight base and rear sight block, and gas tube are Romanian.
Trigger guard, top cover, selector, and rear trunnion are Egyptian.
Front trunnion and bolt are Hungarian
Bolt carrier is Polish.
All other parts are US made for 922r compliance (muzzle brake, trigger parts, receiver, nitrided barrel, and Magpul PMAG)

This is not an entry-level IO or WASR. In the unlikely event that you have an issue, I will fix it at no cost whatsoever.

EDIT: Someone emailed and asked if this was a serialized receiver or not. Yes, NoDak/McKay receivers are all serialized firearms.

title: For Sale:  1896 Ivey Johnson 5 shot top break revolver
postcontent:
This is the Ivey Johnson .38 5 shot top break revolver with trigger safety. The last year patent stamps were of 1896 on the handle butt. Gun is in great condition. It is tight and grips are in excellent  condition. There is what I believe is the serial number under the left handle and it is 4462. You can still see the patent numbers real well on the gun. Most I have found on net are like 20,000 + on up.

If the pictures are too big then open it with something where you can resize the image to about 70%. I have shot .38SW shorts in it ok before, but my research shows these were actually designed to shoot black powder in them until the 1909 models.

My grandfather was a big timber business man from Salem, MO and used to carry  this with him and a 410 shotgun pistol when he took his money to the bank on horseback in the pre-depression days. He was also a deputy sheriiff at one time and later in life became the pastor of the Pentecostal Church that he built in Salem, MO. He gave this gun to my father. It is the last firearm I have left to me by my father who died in 1998.

Thanks,
Terry

The MAC-10 (Military Armament Corporation Model 10, officially the M-10) is a compact blowback operated machine pistol developed by Gordon Ingram in 1964.   It is chambered in either 45 ACP or 9mm.   A two-stage suppressor by Sionics, was designed for the MAC-10, which not only abated the noise created, but made it easier to control on full automatic.

Military Armament Corporation (MAC), based in Powder Springs Georgia from 1970-1976 was the first company to commercially produce the MAC Model 10 (MAC-10).This is the company started by Gordon Ingram that designed and built the first MAC.    MAC marketed a number of different weapons, but the MAC-10 (chambered in 9 mm and later in.45 ACP) and the high cyclic rate (approx. 1600 rpm) MAC-11 (chambered in .380) were its mainstays.   MAC declared bankruptcy in 1976 and went out of business. 

Military Armament Corporation in Stephenville, TX took the MAC design from the Powder Springs plant and redesigned the gun to be "better".  In short they redesigned the trigger mechanism, the safety, and the stock. 

RPB Industries manufactured the only semi auto open bolt variety of the M10 ever made, most were stamped "sM10" but a very few were made with the model stamped as "sapM10" (an abbreviation for semi auto pistol) These few are the only open bolt M10's which are not banned as assault weapons by the state of CA. This is a very rare variant of an extremely hard to come by pistol.

Like new Leupold 4X12 VX1 scope (lifetime warantee) mounted on the top rail and a La Rue Tactical LT130 Bipod adapter and Harris SLM pivoting, adjustable bipod for expert marksmanship. Gun uses 20 round mags. Very few rounds and no hiccups. Comes with a nice sling. Made close by in Fredericksburg, these are guaranteed to have sub MOA accuracy. Quality rig and high end accessories, no junk.

$1700
